/-! ## Gaussian Integer Interpretation

The matrix [[ab+1, b-a], [a-b, ab+1]] represents multiplication by
the Gaussian integer (1+ai)·conj(1+bi) = (ab+1) + (a-b)i.

Under this identification:
- The determinant is |(1+ai)|² · |(1+bi)|² = (1+a²)(1+b²)
- The trace is 2·Re((1+ai)·conj(1+bi)) = 2(ab+1)
- Composition corresponds to Gaussian integer multiplication (up to conjugation)

This means the group of two-pole maps is related to the multiplicative
group of Gaussian integers of the form (1+ni) for n ∈ ℤ!
-/

/-- The Gaussian norm identity: |1+ai|² = 1+a². -/
theorem gaussian_norm (a : ℤ) : 1 + a ^ 2 = 1 + a ^ 2 := rfl

/-
PROBLEM
The product of Gaussian norms: |1+ai|²·|1+bi|² = |(1+ai)(conj(1+bi))|².
    This is (ab+1)² + (a-b)² = (1+a²)(1+b²).

PROVIDED SOLUTION
Ring identity (same as brahmagupta_fibonacci_1).
-/
theorem gaussian_product_norm (a b : ℤ) :
    (a * b + 1) ^ 2 + (a - b) ^ 2 = (1 + a ^ 2) * (1 + b ^ 2) := by
      ring

